[[File:Armenoid Armenian.jpg|thumb|180px|A [[Armenians in Syria|Syrian Armenian]] man of Armenoid type, from ''The Races of Europe: A Sociological Study'' by [[William Zebina Ripley]] (1911)]]
In the [[Scientific racism|racial anthropology]] of the early 20th century, the '''Armenoid type''' is a subtype of the [[Caucasian race]].<ref name="Ripley">{{cite book|last=Ripley|first=William Z.|authorlink=William Z. Ripley|title=[[The Races of Europe (Ripley)|The Races of Europe: A Sociological Study]]|year=1899|publisher=[[D. Appleton & Company]]|page=444}}</ref> According to anthropologist [[Carleton S. Coon|Carleton Coon]],<sup>questionable source</sup> the countries of the northern part of [[Western Asia]], namely [[Anatolia]]/[[Asia Minor]], the [[Caucasus]], [[Iran]], [[Upper Mesopotamia]] and the [[Levant]], were considered the center of distribution of the Armenoid race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://img819.imageshack.us/img819/4152/troeracemap.jpg|title=Carleton Coon, "Racial Distribution map"|accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref>

==Origin==
Prominent [[Nazism|Nazi]] and racial theorist [[Hans F. K. Günther]] used the term '[[Near Eastern]] race' to describe the Armenoid type, and ascribed Near Eastern characteristics to several contemporary peoples, including:  [[Armenians]], [[Jews]], [[Greeks]], [[Georgian people|Georgians]], [[Iranian peoples|Iranians]], [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]], [[Syrians]], and [[Turkish people|Turks]].<ref>Alan E Steinweis. ''Studying the Jew: Scholarly Antisemitism in Nazi Germany''. Harvard University Press, 2008. P. 29.</ref> Günther regarded Jews as people of multiple racial origins but defined the Near Eastern race as their major basis, and described the race's characteristics such as its "commercial spirit" and as being "artful traders" who had strong psychological manipulation capacities that helped their trade, as well as being known to exploit people.<ref>Alan E Steinweis. ''Studying the Jew: Scholarly Antisemitism in Nazi Germany''. Harvard University Press, 2008. P. 29.</ref> Günther's conception has been criticized for [[Pseudoscience|pseudoscientific]] analysis.<ref>Alan E Steinweis. ''Studying the Jew: Scholarly Antisemitism in Nazi Germany''. Harvard University Press, 2008. P. 29.</ref> [[Nazism|Nazis]] historically identified [[Jews]] as within the Armenoid type in the name of the Near Eastern race.<ref>Mitchell B. Hart. Jews & Race: Writings on Identity & Difference, 1880-1940. Lebanon, New Hampshire, USA: Brandeis University Press, 2011. P. 247.</ref> [[Nazism|Nazis]] utilized the Armenoid type in the name of the Near Eastern race, and identified [[Jews]] as a particular group within that type.<ref>Mitchell B. Hart. Jews & Race: Writings on Identity & Difference, 1880-1940. Lebanon, New Hampshire, USA: Brandeis University Press, 2011. P. 247.</ref>

==Physiognomy==
[[File:Armenoid Lebanese.jpg|thumb|200px|A [[Lebanese people|Lebanese]] man of Armenoid type, from Ripley (1911)]]
[[Renato Biasutti]] described the Armenoid race as having: "Opaque-white skin, [[brown hair|brunet hair]] and [[eye color#Brown|eyes]], abundant pilosity; medium stature (166), sturdy body build; wide head with rounded occiput (87); very long face, straight and narrow nose (57) with high bridge; thin lips, narrow eye opening.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dienekes.110mb.com/texts/biasutticaucasoid/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-05-11 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511091339/http://dienekes.110mb.com/texts/biasutticaucasoid/ |archivedate=2012-05-11 |df= }}</ref> 

[[Carleton S. Coon]] wrote that the Armenoid racial type is very similar to the [[Dinaric race]], most probably due to racial mixture with the [[Mediterranean race|Mediterraneans]] (who often have [[olive skin]]) and the [[Alpine race|Alpines]] (who often have brown skin). The only difference is that Armenoids have a slightly darker [[pigmentation]]. He described the Armenoid as a sub-race of the [[Caucasian race|Caucasoid race]].
Armenoids were said to be found throughout [[Eurasia]]. However, the largest concentrations occurred within [[Anatolia]], [[South Caucasus|Transcaucasia]], [[Iran]], and [[Mesopotamia]]. 

Considered to be the "true" [[Caucasus|Caucasians]], Armenoids were relatively tall, usually with [[Brown hair|medium to dark brown]] or [[black hair]], light to medium skin colour, large round eyes that were usually brown; a round, brachycephalic head shape with a straight backing (planocciput) (see [[Cephalic index]]), high cheekbones and non-prominent chins. Lips were full, and noses were often [[aquiline nose|aquiline]]. Large minority of Armenoids have [[blond]] hair and [[eye color#Blue|blue]], [[eye color#Green|green]], or hazel eyes. This racial type was believed to be prevalent among the [[Armenians]], [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]], and [[Iraqi people|Iraqis]].<ref name=WBF>{{cite book|last=Fisher|first=William B.|authorlink=William Bayne Fisher|title=The Middle East and North Africa, Volume 50|year=2003|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=978-1-85743-184-1|page=444|quote=The northern and eastern hill districts [of Iraq] contain many racial elements—Turkish, Persian, and proto-Nordic, with Armenoid strains predominating. [..] the population of the riverine districts of Iraq displays a mixture of Armenoid and Mediterranean elements. North of the Baghdad district the Armenoid strain is dominant.}}</ref><ref name=WBF2>{{cite book|last=Fisher|first=William B.|authorlink=William Bayne Fisher|title=The Middle East: A Physical, Social and Regional Geography|year=1966|publisher=[[Methuen Publishing|Methuen]]|isbn=978-0-416-71510-1|page=96|quote=Armenoid affinities are easily discerned in the peoples of northern and central Iraq.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pP315Mw3S9EC}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=pP315Mw3S9EC&pg=PA444 extract of page 444]</ref> 

==Distribution==
The Armenoid race type exists to the west and north of the [[Arabid race]], and encompasses the modern Armenians, Assyrians, [[Maronite]]s, [[Greeks]], [[Turkish people|Turks]], [[Kurds]], [[Georgians]], Iranians, [[Israelis]], [[Demographics of Syria|Syrians]], [[Druze]], [[Yazidi]]s, [[Shabaks]], [[Mandeans]] and [[Mhallami]],<ref>Review: An Introduction to the Anthropology of the Near East by C. U. Ariëns Kappers, American Anthropologist, 37(35) - Pages 148-49 by W.M. Krogman</ref> together with the ancient ancestors and/or predecessors of these peoples, such as the Assyrians, [[Akkadians]], [[Babylon]]ians, [[Chaldea]]ns, [[Eblaites]], [[Amorites]], [[Canaan]]ites, [[Kassites]], [[Gutians]], [[Hittites]], [[Hattians]], [[Hurrian]]s, [[Phrygia]]ns, [[Lydia]]ns, [[Phoenicia]]ns, [[Carthaginia]]ns, [[Medes]], Persians, [[Scythian]]s,  [[Israelite]]s, [[Samaritan]]s, [[Judean]]s, [[Edomite]]s, [[Moab]]ites, [[Ammonite]]s, [[Philistine]]s, [[Cilician]]s, [[Cappadocian]]s and [[Minoan civilization|Minoans]] among others.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hourani|first=Albert H.|authorlink=Albert Hourani|title=Syria and Lebanon: A Political Essay|year=1946|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|page=96}}</ref>

{{Cquote|It has long been believed by physical anthropologists that the quintessence of Near Eastern brachycephaly is to be found in the Armenians; the racial term Armenoid being named for them. The Armenians have long been established in the territory which is now only partly theirs; they had, before the arrival of the Turks, a powerful kingdom, which covered most of the territory between the Gulf of Alexandretta and the Caucasus.<ref>The Races of Europe by Carleton Stevens Coon - (Chapter XII, section 18)</ref>}}

== Types==
{{Refimprove section|date=July 2017}}
The Armenoid is divided into four types: Armenid, Anatolid, Assyrid, and Caucasid.

'''Assyrid''' - [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]], [[Levant|Levantine people]], [[Ashkenazi Jews]], [[Sicilians]], and the [[Maltese people]] belong to this type. Assyrids are of middling height and generally have a medium build. They are usually considered to have a slight Arabid influence.

'''Caucasid''' - Robust type prevalent among the people of the [[Caucasus]], such as in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], [[Turkey (country)|Turkey]], and even [[Sicily]].

