{{Infobox scientist | name = Stefan Lucks | image = | image_size = 150px | caption = Stefan Lucks in 2006 | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1964|5|10|df=y}} | birth_place = | nationality = [[Germany|German]] | field = [[Computer science]] | work_institution = [[Bauhaus University, Weimar]] | alma_mater = [[University of Göttingen]] | doctoral_advisor = Stephan Waack | thesis_title = Systematische Entwurfsmethoden für praktikable Kryptosysteme | thesis_url = http://num.math.uni-goettingen.de/picap/pdf/E434.pdf | thesis_year = 1997 | doctoral_students = | known_for = attacks on [[Triple DES]], [[Advanced Encryption Standard|AES]], [[LEVIATHAN (cipher)|LEVIATHAN]], and [[E0 (cipher)|E0]] | website = [http://www.uni-weimar.de/de/medien/professuren/mediensicherheit/people/stefan-lucks/ www.uni-weimar.de] }}
'''Stefan Lucks''' is a researcher in the fields of [[communications security]] and [[cryptography]]. Lucks is known for his attack on [[Triple DES]], and for extending [[Lars Knudsen]]'s [[Square attack]] to [[Twofish]], a cipher outside the [[Square (cipher)|Square]] family, thus generalising the attack into [[integral cryptanalysis]]. He has also co-authored attacks on [[Advanced Encryption Standard|AES]], [[LEVIATHAN (cipher)|LEVIATHAN]], and the [[E0 (cipher)|E0]] cipher used in [[Bluetooth]] devices, as well as publishing strong password-based [[key agreement]] schemes.
Lucks graduated from the [[Dortmund University of Technology|University of Dortmund]] in 1992, and received his PhD at the [[University of Göttingen]] in 1997. After leaving the [[University of Mannheim]] Lucks now heads the Chair of Media Security at [[Bauhaus University, Weimar]].
Together with [[Niels Ferguson]], [[Bruce Schneier]] and others he developed the [[Skein (hash function)|Skein]] hash function as a candidate for the [[NIST hash function competition]].
